{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659912"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:16:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:16:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21084"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21084"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13959"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110740"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13959"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92991"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39805"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110740"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows a cross-section of a peripheral nerve stained with haematoxylin and eosin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the connective tissue layer that surrounds individual nerve fascicles?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endoneurium","Perineurium","Neurilemma","Epineurium","Myelin sheath"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eepineurium\u003C/strong\u003E is the outermost connective tissue layer that surrounds the entire peripheral nerve and fills the space between individual nerve fascicles. It consists of dense irregular connective tissue containing collagen fibers, fibroblasts, blood vessels, and adipose tissue. The epineurium provides mechanical protection to the nerve and allows it to stretch and recoil during body movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerineurium\u003C/strong\u003E is the connective tissue layer that surrounds individual nerve fascicles (bundles of nerve fibers). It consists of concentric layers of flattened cells joined by tight junctions, forming a blood-nerve barrier.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoneurium\u003C/strong\u003E is the delicate connective tissue within fascicles that surrounds individual nerve fibers (axons and their Schwann cell coverings). It contains collagen fibers, fibroblasts, capillaries, and tissue fluid.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurilemma\u003C/strong\u003E (also called the sheath of Schwann) refers to the cytoplasm and cell membrane of Schwann cells that surrounds axons in the peripheral nervous system.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyelin sheath\u003C/strong\u003E is the lipid-rich insulating layer formed by Schwann cells that wraps around axons in the peripheral nervous system. In histological preparations, the lipids are often dissolved during processing, leaving clear spaces around axons.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn peripheral nerve histology, these distinct layers can be identified based on their location and appearance. The epineurium is the most external layer surrounding the entire nerve trunk, while the perineurium surrounds individual fascicles, and the endoneurium surrounds individual nerve fibers within fascicles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peripheral nerves are composed of multiple nerve fascicles surrounded by connective tissue layers including epineurium, perineurium, and endoneurium.","Myelinated nerve fibers appear as axons surrounded by myelin sheaths, which appear as clear spaces in routine histological preparations.","Schwann cells produce myelin in the peripheral nervous system and also support unmyelinated axons.","The perineurium forms a protective barrier around nerve fascicles and consists of specialized flattened cells."],"references":["Nervous Tissue: Nerve Bundle. Flikr. Image accessed under CC0 1.0 license: https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/. Accessed at: https://www.flickr.com/photos/146824358@N03/40106758500/","Chapter 7, Nervous tissues. In: Wheater\u2019s Functional Histology. 7th ed. London: Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2023."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92991"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21084"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21819"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21819"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JODzBjlxulXUQVwl6M8Y7dTJQysKKs.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JODzBjlxulXUQVwl6M8Y7dTJQysKKs.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":846}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92991"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-03T20:24:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-03T20:26:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13959"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110740"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"ty